<subSubSection box="[151,288,438,462]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,515,403,462]" box="[151,288,438,462]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<figureCitation box="[151,288,438,462]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 49A–G</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,510,714]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,510,535]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Labrum and premandible as in 
<figureCitation box="[636,740,510,534]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49A</figureCitation>
; pecten epipharyngis with three toothed plates; labral lamella with tight row of 28 teeth; premandible with two apical teeth; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[958,1059,546,570]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49B</figureCitation>
) almost as long as head, pedestal (
<figureCitation box="[159,263,582,606]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49C</figureCitation>
) with small apical spur, stalk of LO twice as long as segment 2, AR 2.14; mandible (
<figureCitation box="[1263,1368,582,606]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49D</figureCitation>
) with slightly angled outer margin, but without lobe; mentum (
<figureCitation box="[799,899,618,642]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49E</figureCitation>
) with toothed margin evenly arched; VM plate with narrow medial gap; posterior end of abdomen as in 
<figureCitation box="[792,891,654,678]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49F</figureCitation>
; anal tubules curled ventrally; posterior parapod with about 60 claws arranged in horseshoe pattern.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="58" pageNumber="59" startId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" targetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" targetPageId="58">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,1500,1552]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,1500,1523]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">FIGURE 49.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Malloch)" baseAuthorityName="Malloch" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[297,612,1500,1522]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Micropsectra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polita">
<emphasis box="[297,500,1500,1522]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Micropsectra polita</emphasis>
(Malloch)
</taxonomicName>
, larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,1633,1945]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1634,1658]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Notes.</emphasis>
Generally fits larval description given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Oliver, D. R. &amp; Dillon, M. E." box="[760,1047,1633,1657]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="199 - 217" refId="ref27177" refString="Oliver, D. R. &amp; Dillon, M. E. (1994) Systematics of some species of Micropsectra (Diptera: Chironomidae) living in low-order streams in southern Ontario, Canada. The Canadian Entomologist, 126, 199 - 217." type="journal article" year="1994">Oliver and Dillon (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, although the AR was outside the lower end of range (2.20–2.49). Cases (
<figureCitation box="[594,696,1669,1693]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1500,1523]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-331@58.[188,1398,767,1478]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 49. Micropsectra polita (Malloch), larva (A–G). A—labrum and premandible; B—antenna; C—antennal pedestal, showing apical spur; D—mandible; E—mentum and VM plates; F—posterior end of abdomen; G—larval cases." pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 49G</figureCitation>
) are made of loose fine detritus, probably attached to rocks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,1633,1945]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,450,1705,1730]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Ecology and habitat.</emphasis>
Larvae have a preference for low order streams with maximum range temperature of 10–18 °C and slow seepage areas (
<bibRefCitation author="Oliver, D. R. &amp; Dillon, M. E." box="[547,798,1741,1765]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" pagination="199 - 217" refId="ref27177" refString="Oliver, D. R. &amp; Dillon, M. E. (1994) Systematics of some species of Micropsectra (Diptera: Chironomidae) living in low-order streams in southern Ontario, Canada. The Canadian Entomologist, 126, 199 - 217." type="journal article" year="1994">Oliver &amp; Dillon 1994</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae occurred in all study streams in large numbers. They were the dominant species of 
<taxonomicName box="[549,709,1777,1801]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chironomidae</taxonomicName>
in study streams.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1436,1633,1945]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,379,1813,1838]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Sampling sites.</emphasis>
We found the larvae inhabiting streams in all the provincial parks and districts located in our study area.
</paragraph>
